---
import { getCollection } from "astro:content";
import { Code } from "astro:components";
import CardGrid from "../components/CardGrid.astro";
import Callout from "../components/Callout.astro";
import DiagramPanel from "../components/DiagramPanel.astro";
import Hero from "../components/Hero.astro";
import SiteLayout from "../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";
import { sitePath } from "../utils/sitePath";

const examples = (await getCollection("examples"))
  .filter((example) => example.data.kind === "contract")
  .sort((left, right) => left.data.order - right.data.order);

const exampleCards = examples.map((example) => ({
  description: example.data.description,
  href: sitePath(`examples/${example.data.routeSlug}/`),
  label: "Open example",
  title: example.data.title,
  tone: "fit" as const,
}));

const demoCommands = `cd Site/public/examples/swift-cli-maintenance
personakit validate --root personakit-root
personakit contract --root personakit-root --session cli-maintenance
personakit export --root personakit-root --session cli-maintenance`;
---

<SiteLayout
  title="PersonaKit"
  description="You told the agent to stay read-only. It edited anyway. PersonaKit makes the session boundary a contract you can inspect before work starts."
>
  <Hero
    title="You told the agent to stay read-only. It edited anyway."
    lede="PersonaKit writes the boundary down as a contract you can read before the agent starts."
    actions={[
      { href: sitePath("start-here/"), label: "Start Here" },
    ]}
  />

  <main>
    <section>
      <h2>What PersonaKit Is</h2>
      <p class="section-lede">PersonaKit is a session-start layer between you and your coding agent. Before work begins it resolves a contract you can inspect, commit, and hand off.</p>
      <p class="repo-chip"><span class="chip-was">in chat</span><span class="chip-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</span><span class="chip-now">in the repo</span></p>

      <div class="contract-tiles" aria-label="The four things a contract makes explicit">
        <article class="tile">
          <span class="tile-dot dot-who" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <h3>Who's acting</h3>
          <p>The role, and the work it should not take on.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="tile">
          <span class="tile-dot dot-allow" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <h3>What's allowed</h3>
          <p>The capabilities authorized for this work mode.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="tile">
          <span class="tile-dot dot-forbid" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <h3>What's forbidden</h3>
          <p>The actions held off-limits for this session.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="tile">
          <span class="tile-dot dot-stop" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <h3>When to stop</h3>
          <p>The review gates where the work pauses.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
      <div class="tile-refs" aria-label="Where each part is defined">
        <a href={`${sitePath("learn/")}#persona`}>persona</a>
        <div class="ref-bracket">
          <a href={`${sitePath("learn/")}#skills`}>skill authorization</a>
        </div>
        <a href={`${sitePath("learn/")}#directive`}>directive</a>
      </div>

      <ul class="not-this">
        <li><strong>Not a task list.</strong> It defines how to do the work, not what to do.</li>
        <li><strong>Not a memory system.</strong> It gives the session a starting contract; it does not remember across them.</li>
        <li><strong>Not the worker.</strong> Your coding agent does the work; PersonaKit sets the boundary it works under.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Sound Familiar?</h2>
      <p class="section-lede">The problem is not that agents lack instructions. Capable agents, carrying memory and skills and compressed chat history, still need an operator-visible boundary for the work they are about to do.</p>
      <div class="scenarios">
        <article class="scenario">
          <div class="scenario-body">
            <h3>The boundary erodes</h3>
            <p>You asked for a code review. The agent found something obvious and fixed it while it was there. You wanted findings; you got a diff.</p>
          </div>
          <p class="scenario-fix"><strong>With PersonaKit:</strong> the review session declares implementation forbidden, and that is visible before work starts. <a href={sitePath("examples/review-session/")}>See the contract &rarr;</a></p>
        </article>
        <article class="scenario">
          <div class="scenario-body">
            <h3>The setup disappears</h3>
            <p>The first ten minutes go to explaining the rules: leave the CLI output alone, flag any public API change, stop before pushing. Next session, same rules, same typing. The work mode lived in chat, and chat ended.</p>
          </div>
          <p class="scenario-fix"><strong>With PersonaKit:</strong> the rules live in the repo, and the session starts with the contract already resolved. <a href={sitePath("examples/cli-maintenance/")}>See the contract &rarr;</a></p>
        </article>
        <article class="scenario">
          <div class="scenario-body">
            <h3>The teammate doesn't know the rules</h3>
            <p>Someone else runs the agent against the same codebase. They never saw the careful review-only lane you set up. Nothing carries that boundary to them, and things happen that were not supposed to.</p>
          </div>
          <p class="scenario-fix"><strong>With PersonaKit:</strong> the contract is a committed file. Anyone can read it, run it, and hand off from the same starting boundary.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="scenario">
          <div class="scenario-body">
            <h3>The capable agent does the wrong extra thing</h3>
            <p>The agent has git, file editing, and bash. For this session, only file reading was appropriate. Nothing said so, and it did what it could rather than what you meant.</p>
          </div>
          <p class="scenario-fix"><strong>With PersonaKit:</strong> the contract declares what is authorized, not just what is available, so the agent knows the boundary before it starts. <a href={sitePath("examples/mcp-grounding/")}>See the contract &rarr;</a></p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="principle">
      <p class="principle-line">Availability is not authorization.</p>
      <p class="principle-gloss">A tool being reachable does not mean it should run in this session. The contract decides.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="band">
      <h2>How The Pieces Fit</h2>
      <p class="section-lede">PersonaKit is the session-start resolver. Prompts describe the task, reusable PersonaKit content defines the pieces, and PersonaKit composes them into a resolved boundary for the handoff.</p>
      <div class="contract-flow" aria-label="Session prompt, PersonaKit contract resolution, and agent work stages">
        <article class="flow-stage">
          <p class="stage-kicker">1. Start The Session</p>
          <h3>Prompt + Session</h3>
          <p>The operator asks for work and chooses the PersonaKit session that should govern it.</p>
          <div class="flow-tags" aria-label="Session inputs">
            <span>prompt</span>
            <span>session id</span>
          </div>
        </article>
        <span class="flow-arrow" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        <article class="flow-stage persona-stage">
          <p class="stage-kicker">2. Resolve The Contract</p>
          <h3>PersonaKit</h3>
          <p>Deterministically composes persona, directive, kits, intents, essentials, references, and skill authorization into one inspectable contract.</p>
          <div class="flow-tags" aria-label="Resolved contract parts">
            <span>role</span>
            <span>rules</span>
            <span>allowed skills</span>
            <span>stop points</span>
          </div>
        </article>
        <span class="flow-arrow" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        <article class="flow-stage">
          <p class="stage-kicker">3. Work Under It</p>
          <h3>Agent + Skills</h3>
          <p>The person at the controls or the harness passes the exported contract into the coding agent or host surface. Skills and tools can help, but only when the contract authorizes them.</p>
          <div class="flow-tags" aria-label="Worker surfaces">
            <span>harness</span>
            <span>skills</span>
            <span>tools</span>
          </div>
        </article>
      </div>
      <p class="section-note"><strong>PersonaKit Studio</strong> sits on the same contract model as a visual inspection and pack-maintenance surface. The CLI and static example roots remain the primary path for validating, inspecting, and exporting contracts. Learn introduces the guided ReleaseDesk lab once the basic contract model is in place.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Run One Contract</h2>
      <div class="grid two">
        <article class="card">
          <h3>Try The Demo</h3>
          <Code code={demoCommands} lang="bash" theme="github-dark" />
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <h3>What It Proves</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>The authored root is valid.</li>
            <li>The session resolves deterministically.</li>
            <li>Code editing is authorized for this work mode.</li>
            <li>Deployment and autonomous loops are forbidden.</li>
            <li>The handoff context is visible before work starts.</li>
          </ul>
          <a class="button-link" href={sitePath("start-here/")}>Run the first contract</a>
        </article>
      </div>
      <p class="section-note">These commands assume a clone of the PersonaKit repo, where the example root lives under <code>Site/public/examples</code>. In your own project, point <code>--root</code> at your <code>.personakit</code> folder.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Think In Contracts</h2>
      <DiagramPanel
        src={sitePath("diagrams/personakit-operating-contract.svg")}
        alt="Session, persona, directive, kits, intents, essentials, references, and skill authorization resolving into an operating contract for an agent."
      />
      <Callout>
        <p><strong>Same inputs, same contract, every time.</strong> Resolution is deterministic, so the boundary the agent receives is one you can review before any work happens.</p>
      </Callout>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Example Roots</h2>
      <p class="section-lede">After the Start Here guide, use these roots as practical patterns for recurring work modes.</p>
      <CardGrid cards={exampleCards} columns="two" />
    </section>

    <section class="band">
      <h2>Use It When The Work Mode Repeats</h2>
      <div class="grid two">
        <article class="card">
          <h3>Good Fit</h3>
          <p>Use it at the start of a repeated session when a prompt plus skills is not enough: role, rules, allowed capabilities, stop points, and proof need to be inspectable before work begins.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <h3>Bad Fit</h3>
          <p>Skip it when you only need a one-off prompt, a skill or tool inside an already-running conversation, a place to track tasks, or exploratory planning before the work mode is clear.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
      <p class="section-action"><a class="button-link" href={sitePath("when-to-use/")}>Check fit before authoring</a></p>
    </section>
  </main>
</SiteLayout>

<style>
  .repo-chip {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 10px;
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 14px;
  }

  .chip-was {
    color: var(--muted);
    text-decoration: line-through;
  }

  .chip-arrow {
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .chip-now {
    padding: 3px 11px;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 999px;
    background: var(--band);
    font-weight: 650;
  }

  .contract-tiles {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: 14px;
    margin: 20px 0 0;
  }

  .tile {
    min-width: 0;
    padding: 16px;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 8px;
    background: var(--paper);
  }

  .tile h3 {
    margin: 10px 0 6px;
  }

  .tile p {
    max-width: none;
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 15px;
  }

  .tile-dot {
    display: inline-block;
    width: 10px;
    height: 10px;
    border-radius: 50%;
  }

  .dot-who { background: var(--blue); }
  .dot-allow { background: var(--green); }
  .dot-forbid { background: var(--red); }
  .dot-stop { background: var(--amber); }

  .tile-refs {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: 14px;
    margin-top: 8px;
  }

  .tile-refs > a {
    text-align: center;
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 13px;
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .ref-bracket {
    grid-column: 2 / span 2;
    padding-top: 7px;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
    text-align: center;
  }

  .ref-bracket a {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 13px;
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .tile-refs a:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  .not-this {
    display: grid;
    gap: 8px;
    max-width: 760px;
    margin: 26px 0 0;
    padding: 0;
    list-style: none;
  }

  .not-this li {
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .not-this strong {
    color: var(--ink);
  }

  .scenarios {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: 16px;
    margin-top: 18px;
  }

  .scenario {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 8px;
    background: var(--paper);
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .scenario-body {
    flex: 1;
    padding: 18px 18px 14px;
  }

  .scenario-body h3 {
    margin: 0 0 8px;
  }

  .scenario-body p {
    max-width: none;
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .scenario-fix {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 14px 18px;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
    background: var(--band);
    font-size: 15px;
  }

  .scenario-fix strong {
    color: var(--blue);
  }

  .scenario-fix a {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-weight: 650;
    white-space: nowrap;
  }

  .principle {
    margin: 44px 0;
  }

  .principle-line {
    margin: 0 0 6px;
    font-size: 26px;
    font-weight: 800;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
  }

  .principle-gloss {
    max-width: 620px;
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 17px;
  }

  @media (max-width: 760px) {
    .contract-tiles {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    }

    .scenarios {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .tile-refs {
      display: flex;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
      justify-content: center;
      gap: 8px 16px;
    }

    .ref-bracket {
      padding-top: 0;
      border-top: 0;
    }
  }

  .section-lede {
    max-width: 760px;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 18px;
  }

  .section-action {
    margin: 0;
  }

  .section-note {
    max-width: 760px;
    margin: 0 0 18px;
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .section-action .button-link {
    margin-top: 18px;
  }

  .contract-flow {
    display: grid;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 16px;
    grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) auto minmax(0, 1.08fr) auto minmax(0, 1fr);
    margin: 24px 0 22px;
  }

  .flow-stage {
    min-width: 0;
    min-height: 100%;
    padding: 18px;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 8px;
    background: #fff;
    box-shadow: 0 10px 24px rgb(32 36 40 / 5%);
  }

  .flow-stage h3 {
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }

  .flow-stage p:last-of-type {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .stage-kicker {
    margin-bottom: 8px;
    color: var(--blue);
    font-size: 13px;
    font-weight: 750;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .flow-tags {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 7px;
    margin-top: 16px;
  }

  .flow-tags span {
    padding: 4px 8px;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 999px;
    background: #f7f9fb;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 13px;
    font-weight: 650;
  }

  .flow-arrow {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    align-self: center;
    width: 22px;
    height: 22px;
    color: var(--blue);
    font-weight: 850;
    line-height: 1;
  }

  .flow-arrow::before {
    content: "→";
    font-size: 22px;
  }

  .persona-stage {
    border-color: #8db3c9;
    background: #eef6fa;
  }

  @media (max-width: 960px) {
    .contract-flow {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .flow-arrow {
      justify-self: start;
      margin-left: 18px;
    }

    .flow-arrow::before {
      content: "↓";
      font-size: 20px;
    }
  }
</style>
